columns_to_check = ['MonthlyCharges', 'TotalCharges', 'tenure']

# Create subplots for each column
fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=len(columns_to_check), figsize=(15, 5))

# Loop through each column and create box plots
for i, col in enumerate(columns_to_check):
    sns.boxplot(x=df[col], ax=axes[i])
    axes[i].set_title(f'Box Plot of {col}')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Outlier detection using IQR method
outliers = {}
for col in columns_to_check:
    Q1 = df[col].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = df[col].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1

    lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

    outliers[col] = df[(df[col] < lower_bound) | (df[col] > upper_bound)]

# Print rows containing outliers for each column
for col, outlier_df in outliers.items():
    print(f'Outliers in {col}:')
    print(outlier_df)

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

def category_summary(df, col_name, churn_col, plot=False):
    print('***', col_name, '***')
    value_counts = df[col_name].value_counts()
    ratios = 100 * value_counts / len(df)

    churn_counts = df.groupby(col_name)[churn_col].value_counts().unstack().fillna(0)
    churn_ratios = 100 * churn_counts.div(churn_counts.sum(axis=1), axis=0)

    summary_df = pd.concat([value_counts, ratios, churn_counts, churn_ratios], axis=1)
    summary_df.columns = [f'{col_name}_Counts', f'{col_name}_Ratio (%)', 'Churn_0', 'Churn_1', 'Churn_0_Ratio (%)', 'Churn_1_Ratio (%)']

    if plot:
        colors = sns.color_palette('pastel')[0:len(summary_df)]

        # Create a 1x2 grid of subplots with a custom figsize
        fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 5))

        for i, ax in enumerate(axes):
            if i < len(summary_df):
                current_col = summary_df.columns[i]

                if "Ratio" in current_col:
                    sns.barplot(x=summary_df.index, y=current_col, data=summary_df, palette='pastel', ax=ax)
                    ax.set_title(f'{col_name} {current_col}')
                else:
                    sns.countplot(x=col_name, hue=churn_col, data=df, palette='pastel', ax=ax)
                    ax.set_title(f'{col_name} Churn Distribution')
                    ax.legend(title=churn_col)

                ax.set_xticklabels(ax.get_xticklabels(), rotation=45)

        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.show()

# Example usage for categorical_columns and the 'Churn' column

churn_column = 'Churn'

for col in categorical_columns:
    category_summary(df, col, churn_column, plot=True)

# Assuming you have your DataFrame df with the relevant columns
# List of categorical columns
categorical_columns = [
    'gender', 'InternetService', 'PaymentMethod', 'SeniorCitizen',
    'Partner', 'Dependents', 'PhoneService', 'MultipleLines',
    'OnlineSecurity', 'OnlineBackup', 'DeviceProtection', 'TechSupport',
    'StreamingTV', 'StreamingMovies', 'Contract', 'PaperlessBilling'
]

# Initialize a list to store statistically significant columns
significant_columns = []

# Set the significance level (alpha)
alpha = 0.05

# Loop through the categorical columns and perform chi-squared tests
for col in categorical_columns:
    # Create a contingency table
    contingency_table = pd.crosstab(df[col], df['Churn'])

    # Perform the chi-squared test
    chi2, p, _, _ = chi2_contingency(contingency_table)

    # Check if the p-value is less than alpha (i.e., statistically significant)
    if p < alpha:
        significant_columns.append(col)

# Print the significant columns
print("Statistically Significant Categorical Columns:")
print(significant_columns)

# Use feature selection to select the top-k most important features
# Assuming 'Churn' is your target variable

models = {
    "Logistic Regression": LogisticRegression(),
    "Random Forest": RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=42),
    "Decision Tree": DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42),
    "SVM": SVC(),
    "XGBoost": XGBClassifier(random_state=42),
    "K-Nearest Neighbors": KNeighborsClassifier(),
    "Naive Bayes": GaussianNB(),
    "Gradient Boosting": GradientBoostingClassifier(),
    "LightGBM": LGBMClassifier()
}

best_model = None
best_accuracy = 0.0

for model_name, model in models.items():
    # Train the model using the selected features
    X_train_selected = sfm.transform(X_train)
    X_test_selected = sfm.transform(X_test)

    model.fit(X_train_selected, y_train)

    # Evaluate the model
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test_selected)
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)

    print(f"{model_name} Accuracy: {accuracy:.2f}")

    # Check if this model has the highest accuracy so far
    if accuracy > best_accuracy:
        best_accuracy = accuracy
        best_model = model_name

print(f"The best model is: {best_model} with accuracy {best_accuracy:.2f}")

Examples
--------

    The simplest way to use nbconvert is

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to html

            Options include ['asciidoc', 'custom', 'html', 'latex', 'markdown', 'notebook', 'pdf', 'python', 'rst', 'script', 'slides', 'webpdf'].

            > jupyter nbconvert --to latex mynotebook.ipynb

            Both HTML and LaTeX support multiple output templates. LaTeX includes
            'base', 'article' and 'report'.  HTML includes 'basic', 'lab' and
            'classic'. You can specify the flavor of the format used.

            > jupyter nbconvert --to html --template lab mynotebook.ipynb

            You can also pipe the output to stdout, rather than a file

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --stdout

            PDF is generated via latex

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to pdf

            You can get (and serve) a Reveal.js-powered slideshow

            > jupyter nbconvert myslides.ipynb --to slides --post serve

            Multiple notebooks can be given at the command line in a couple of
            different ways:

            > jupyter nbconvert notebook*.ipynb
            > jupyter nbconvert notebook1.ipynb notebook2.ipynb

            or you can specify the notebooks list in a config file, containing::

                c.NbConvertApp.notebooks = ["my_notebook.ipynb"]

            > jupyter nbconvert --config mycfg.py

To see all available configurables, use `--help-all`.
